Patch Set 4:

I had a hard time figuring out exactly what's going on here.

There's a difference between (a) checking the maximum value that can be stored in a DB as a signed 4 bit integer, from (b) passing the DB an integral value that it can't handle.  We seem to be worried about (b), but this fix focuses on (a).  Now, in practice, (a) <= (b), so in one sense, making (b) smaller than it strictly speaking has to be will prevent us from making the error, but it still leaves an open question about why we're limited to (a).

I poked around a bit and it looks like the argument to the .limit() qualifier in sqlalchemy has to be a sqlalchemy Integer type, which maps to the standard SQL INTEGER type, which has a max value of 2**31-1.  So the limitation is based on the SQL language standard.

Maybe this was obvious to everyone else; if so, feel free to ignore.  Otherwise I think it would be a good idea to clarify the docstring in _validate_db_int to reflect that we're respecting max value for the SQL INTEGER type.

Patch Set 5:

Well, my thought is that the limit is a SQL thing, not a database thing, and the docstring makes it sound like a database thing (see Kairat's comment there).  But I don't feel strongly enough about this to hold up the patch if everyone else thinks it's fine the way it is.
